{
  "texts": [
    "The authors' approach is novel in utilising TL from an ImageNet (Deng et al. 2009) pre-trained model to mitigate the scarcity of training data, where the low-layer network parameters were frozen, and only the high-layer parameters were retrained with a limited set of microfossil images.",
    "This modification focuses on the effective use of residual blocks, including four key blocks (Conv2_x, Conv3_x, Conv4_x, and Conv5_x), which proved crucial in addressing the gradient vanishing problem and enhancing model stability and accuracy, achieving near-perfect classification with training with just 50 images per taxon.",
    "The study did, however, rely on synthetic augmentation methods, which may not fully capture the natural variability of microfossil textures and structures, potentially affecting model robustness in real-world applications.",
    "These studies highlight the feasibility of DL techniques for tackling complex classification challenges within micropaleontology, significantly advancing the field's capability to analyze and interpret large amounts of paleontological data.",
    "Lastly, Godbillot et al. (2024) present a method for the automated detection of siliceous biominerals in environmental samples using a fine-tuned ResNet-50 Convolutional Neural Network."
  ]
}